<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-04-25T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-04-25T05:00:00-05:00" n="322" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2632</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-25T11:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1916, 11 a. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 27, 8.10 a.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3805. Your 2927.<note n="1" xml:id="d322fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_239">p.
                                    239</ref>.</note> It occurs to me you might think <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName> meant all ships.
                                Although he used word “ships” only, he plainly meant and I
                                understood him to refer only to freight ships. Of course he was
                                speaking informally and indefinitely. In my conversations with
                                    <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName> we speak
                                English, a language he apparently speaks well, but says himself that
                                his vocabulary is limited. My last conversation with Chancellor was
                                in German, conversation before that in English, and sometimes
                                Chancellor speaks French, and sometimes he speaks German and I
                                English. Of course I have to speak in language he desires. I recall
                                that <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName> also said
                                that sinking merchant ships without notice in war zone was their
                                answer to England’s illegal blockade of Germany.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>